                    <h3>Diverse Roles and Significance of ASL Letters H, I, J, K, L, M, N</h3>
                    <p>In American Sign Language (ASL), the letters H, I, J, K, L, M, and N are not only key for finger
                        spelling but also possess unique features and cultural relevance. Let's explore the distinct
                        aspects of these ASL letters:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Letter H:</strong> The 'H' in ASL is notable for its open, parallel finger
                            positioning, often used in signs needing a sense of openness or alignment.</li>
                        <li><strong>Letter I:</strong> The 'I' in ASL, represented by a pinky finger, is unique in its
                            simplicity and is often employed in signs that require a subtle or delicate touch.</li>
                        <li><strong>Letter J:</strong> The 'J' in ASL involves a dynamic movement, tracing the letter in
                            the air. This represents one of the few instances where motion is used to form a letter in
                            the ASL alphabet.</li>
                        <li><strong>Letter K:</strong> The 'K' in ASL stands out with its two-fingered V-shape and thumb
                            placement, used in various signs that require a sense of division or distinction.</li>
                        <li><strong>Letter L:</strong> The 'L' in ASL is easily recognizable and versatile, often seen
                            in educational settings due to its clear and simple structure.</li>
                        <li><strong>Letter M:</strong> The 'M' in ASL, formed with three fingers over the thumb, is
                            distinctive for its more complex handshape, often used in signs with layered or nuanced
                            meanings.</li>
                        <li><strong>Letter N:</strong> The 'N' in ASL, similar to 'M' but with two fingers over the
                            thumb, is versatile in its use and is a common element in many compound signs.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>These letters, with their diverse handshapes and roles, enrich the expressiveness and depth of
                        American Sign Language, highlighting its complexity and cultural significance.</p>
