                <h2>Letter H</h2>
                <p>The 'H' in ASL is created by extending the index and middle fingers while keeping the rest of the
                    fingers curled into the palm. The thumb should be folded over the ring and pinky fingers. This
                    gesture requires careful finger placement for clear communication.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Initial Hand Position:</strong> Start with your hand open, all fingers extended and palm
                        facing forward.</li>
                    <li><strong>Extend Index and Middle Fingers:</strong> Extend your index and middle fingers straight
                        out, keeping them close together, side by side.</li>
                    <li><strong>Curling Ring and Pinky Fingers:</strong> Curl your ring and pinky fingers into your
                        palm. They should be held firmly against the palm.</li>
                    <li><strong>Thumb Positioning:</strong> Fold your thumb over the ring and pinky fingers, resting it
                        against the middle segment of the ring finger.</li>
                    <li><strong>Ensure Clarity:</strong> Keep the 'H' sign clear by maintaining the index and middle
                        fingers fully extended and parallel. The hand should be steady, and the sign held at eye level
                        for visibility.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Practice forming the 'H' sign multiple times to ensure precision and clarity. This letter is crucial
                    for many words in ASL and is a fundamental part of ASL alphabetic signs.</p>
