                <h2>Letter I</h2>
                <p>The 'I' in ASL is represented by extending the little (pinky) finger while keeping the rest of the
                    fingers curled into the palm, and the thumb across the front. This sign requires precision in finger
                    isolation for clear communication.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Initial Hand Position:</strong> Start with your hand open, palm facing yourself.</li>
                    <li><strong>Extend Pinky Finger:</strong> Extend your pinky finger straight up, keeping it isolated
                        and elevated.</li>
                    <li><strong>Curl Other Fingers:</strong> Curl your index, middle, and ring fingers into your palm.
                        They should be held tightly against the palm.</li>
                    <li><strong>Thumb Positioning:</strong> Place your thumb across the front, resting against or
                        slightly over the middle segment of the index finger.</li>
                    <li><strong>Ensure Clarity:</strong> Keep the 'I' sign clear by maintaining the pinky finger fully
                        extended. The hand should be steady, and the sign held at eye level for visibility.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Repeat the formation of the 'I' sign multiple times, checking in a mirror to ensure accuracy. The
