                <h2>Letter J</h2>
                <p>The 'J' in ASL is unique as it involves a motion. It's represented by drawing a 'J' in the air with
                    your pinky finger. This sign starts with a similar hand position to the letter 'I', then adds a
                    downward motion to complete the 'J' shape.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Initial Hand Position:</strong> Begin with your hand open, palm facing yourself. Extend
                        your pinky finger upwards, just like the sign for 'I'.</li>
                    <li><strong>Draw the 'J':</strong> With your pinky finger extended, draw a 'J' in the air. Start at
                        the top and bring your hand down and then curve forward.</li>
                    <li><strong>Curl Other Fingers:</strong> Keep your other fingers - the index, middle, and ring
                        fingers - curled into your palm throughout the motion.</li>
                    <li><strong>Thumb Positioning:</strong> Place your thumb across the front, resting against or over
                        the middle segment of the index finger, ensuring it doesn't obstruct the motion of the 'J'.</li>
                    <li><strong>Motion Clarity:</strong> Ensure the motion is smooth and clear, representing the letter
                        'J' accurately. The downward stroke should be straight, followed by a distinct curve at the
                        bottom.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Practice the 'J' sign several times to get the motion fluid and precise. This dynamic sign is
                    essential in ASL finger spelling and adds diversity to the language's handshapes.</p>
