                <h2>Letter K</h2>
                <p>The 'K' in ASL is formed by positioning the index and middle fingers to create a right angle, with
                    the thumb extended between them. This sign requires precise finger placement to differentiate it
                    from similar signs.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Initial Hand Position:</strong> Start with your hand open, fingers spread apart, and
                        palm facing sideways.</li>
                    <li><strong>Index and Middle Fingers:</strong> Raise your index and middle fingers, keeping them
                        together. Then, split them to form a right angle, with the index finger pointing up and the
                        middle finger pointing forward.</li>
                    <li><strong>Thumb Positioning:</strong> Place your thumb up between the index and middle fingers,
                        touching the middle segment of the middle finger. The thumb acts as a support, keeping the
                        fingers in the right angle position.</li>
                    <li><strong>Curling Other Fingers:</strong> Curl your ring and pinky fingers into your palm. They
                        should be held firmly against the palm, out of sight, to emphasize the shape of the 'K'.</li>
                    <li><strong>Ensure Clarity:</strong> Maintain the right angle between the index and middle fingers
                        clearly. The hand should be steady, and the sign held at eye level for visibility.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Practicing the 'K' sign is important for its unique structure. Repeat the formation several times,
                    checking in a mirror for accuracy. This letter is crucial in ASL as it has a distinct shape compared
