                <h2>Letter M</h2>
                <p>The 'M' in ASL is represented by tucking the thumb underneath the first three fingers (index, middle,
                    and ring fingers) while the pinky remains extended. This sign mimics the shape of the letter 'M'
                    with the three fingers over the thumb.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Initial Hand Position:</strong> Start with your hand open, all fingers extended, and
                        palm facing yourself.</li>
                    <li><strong>Thumb Positioning:</strong> Place your thumb under your index, middle, and ring fingers,
                        slightly towards the palm.</li>
                    <li><strong>Curling Fingers:</strong> Curl your index, middle, and ring fingers down over your
                        thumb, holding it in place.</li>
                    <li><strong>Pinky Extension:</strong> Keep your pinky finger extended straight out. It should be the
                        only finger not touching the thumb.</li>
                    <li><strong>Ensure Clarity:</strong> Make sure the three fingers are securely over the thumb and the
                        pinky is clearly extended to accurately represent the letter 'M'.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Practicing the 'M' sign is important for its unique structure. This letter is a fundamental part of
